## Appendix D.1: Recovered Field Intelligence

Unlock after first Faction encounter or Paradox **5+**

**UNLOCK AFTER FIRST FACTION ENCOUNTER OR**

**PARADOX 5+**

These documents were recovered from Faction operatives, abandoned outposts, and the margins of other Echoes' Chronicles. Reading them is free. Using them costs Coherence. The Faction being studied can sense when their methods are understood — and they adjust accordingly.

**Mechanical hook:** if you have read a memo before the encounter it describes, you may spend **1 Coherence** when that Faction appears to invoke its contents. Gain **+1** on your next Drive Off, Negotiate, or Escape roll against them. You cannot invoke the same memo twice in the same campaign.

---

### MEMO: The Dermestid Protocol

*Source: Recovered from Loop Authority Sector 7, Bureau of Historical Coherence. Classification Level 4.*

"The Dermestid sub-routine manifests as a swarm of localized CTH-constructs. They ingest the Potentiality of un-Anchored events. They strip the meat of the narrative — sensory details, emotional resonance, secondary characters — until only the Bone remains. A clean skeleton is a stable history. Do not mourn the meat.

The sub-routine is deployed when an Echo's Paradox signature generates sufficient temporal noise to warrant structural intervention. The process is not punitive. It is sanitation. The Auditor who submitted this report has since been normalized. His file is consistent."

*Mechanical hook: spend **1 Coherence** when an Authority Agent appears to invoke this memo. Gain **+1** on your next Drive Off or Escape roll — you recognize the Dermestid's behavioral pattern before it begins.*

---

### MEMO: The Toxo-Glitch Manifesto

*Source: Signal-jammed broadcast recovered from Chronoclast frequency. Author: The Broken Watchmaker.*

"When you're infected with the Gordian logic, your senses finally align with the truth of the Chronoverse. You realize that 'Time' isn't a solid floor — it's a deep, dark ocean of harmonics. You jump into the Seam not to die, but to finally breathe.

The Authority calls this suicidal. They have it backward. The world outside the Fracture is the desert. The Shattering is the water. The Causal Fear response they've spent centuries cultivating in you? That's not instinct. That's a leash. The Toxo-Glitch cuts it.

Find the Seam. Jump. The Revel will catch you. Or it won't. Either way you'll finally feel something real."

*Mechanical hook: spend **1 Coherence** when a Chronoclast appears to invoke this memo. Gain **+1** on your next Negotiate roll — you understand the aesthetic they're trying to create, and you can offer to be interesting.*

---

### MEMO: The Sacculina Directive

*Source: Recovered from Scionfall Herald's intake documentation, distributed to displaced persons in Sector 9 processing.*

"We do not remove your desire. We simply redirect it. The barnacle crab does not miss its reproductive organs after integration — it only loves the parasite. We offer you the same liberation.

What you call 'wanting to return home' is a source of constant suffering. We offer you relief from the wanting. What remains after our procedure: the ability to eat, to rest, to exist without the fever of longing. You will still feel. You will simply feel less.

We have found that most clients, in retrospect, wish they had come to us sooner. We are not the end. We are the reduction of noise to bearable levels.

One perfect memory. Warm. Safe. Yours. You get to keep it. Isn't that what you wanted? Just one thing to stay?"

*Mechanical hook: spend **1 Coherence** when a Scionfall Herald appears to invoke this memo. Gain **+1** on your next ENDURE roll to resist their Nullwave — you recognize the warmth as engineered, which doesn't make it easier to refuse, but makes the refusal slightly more possible.*

---

### MEMO: Vitrification Scars — Clinical Advisory

*Source: Scionfall Directive, Office of Ultimate Compassion, Cryonic Preservation Division. Requires Mercy Clearance.*

"Despite our best engineering, Perfect Vitrification remains an asymptote. The act of suspending a consciousness across the void between seconds imposes a thermal-causal shock. We have identified the resulting pathology as the Vitrification Scar.

During the thaw, CTH-proteins occasionally fail to resonate at the host's Anchor frequency, resulting in Mnemonic Brittle-Failure. The memory isn't forgotten — it is shattered into jagged, crystalline fragments. When the Echo attempts to access a vitrified memory, the sharp edges cause secondary trauma to the surrounding Chronicle.

Symptomatology: the Glass Voice (metallic ring when speaking of the vitrified period), Sharp Retrospection (actual physical pain on recall), and Mnemonic Bleeding (composite hallucination where vitrified memories merge with adjacent ones).

The Office of Ultimate Compassion acknowledges these outcomes. We are very sorry. We are always very sorry."

*Mechanical hook: spend **1 Coherence** when a Scionfall Herald appears to invoke this memo. Gain **+1** on your next Escape roll — their own documentation contradicts their pitch of painless peace, and you can use that contradiction as a lever.*

## Appendix E: Captivity Vignettes

Optional extended scenes for Faction capture.

Optional extended scenes for Faction capture. Use these only if you want an extended solo roleplay of a specific capture, or if a quick resolution doesn't serve the story you're building. Otherwise: one roll is enough. The game doesn't require these.

**Church: Harmonic Crucifixion**

You've been captured by Church Templars. They bind you in a causal contradiction — forcing you to witness yourself failing to save someone you love, repeatedly, until your waveform breaks and the Paradox can be harvested. Before you begin, establish: which Memory are they targeting (preferably one connected to your Anchor)? Who are you failing to save in the loop? What is the exact moment of failure?

**THE LOOP**

Each iteration, you experience the full Memory up to the moment of failure. Then it resets. You remember all previous iterations. Roll **2d6** + ENDURE vs. **Difficulty 10** for each loop:

 **10+** Hold. Reduce your Paradox by 1 (they

harvest it). Lose 1 Coherence. You may attempt escape after 3 loops.

 **7-9** Weaken. They harvest 1 Paradox. Lose 1

Coherence. Cannot escape yet.

 **6-** Break. They harvest 2 Paradox. Lose 2

Coherence. One Active Memory related to this scene becomes Fading. After 3 loops regardless of result, you may attempt escape. Roll **2d6** + DISRUPT or SYNC (**Difficulty 10**):

 **10+** Break free. Templars release you —you're

no longer useful. Take Scar: Phantom Screams.

 **7-9** Escape. But they Mark you. They'll hunt you

specifically next encounter.

 **6-** Remain captured. Three more loops. Then

choose: automatic release (you're exhausted and useless), or undergo Lockstep Binding and become a Templar (character retired to NPC status).

**Authority: Loop Containment Protocol**

Reality has stuttered. The same scene repeats. You're trapped in a Clone Loop while the Authority runs their normalization protocol. Define the scene being looped: Where are you? What action are you attempting? What's the basic structure of the **5-10** minute loop?

**ITERATION MECHANICS**

Start Iteration Counter at 0. Each loop, increment by 1. The Difficulty of your escape attempt decreases as the pattern becomes clearer — but your memories are degrading. Roll **2d6** + OBSERVE each iteration (**Difficulty 10** minus Iteration Count):

 **10+** Notice the pattern. You can attempt to

break the loop. No memory loss this iteration.

 **7-9** Something's wrong. Can't quite pin it

down. Choose one Active Memory related to this scene — it becomes Fading.

 **6-** Don't notice. The loop feels natural. One

Active Memory becomes Fading, or if all are already Fading, one Fading becomes Lost.

After noticing the pattern, attempt escape: Roll **2d6** + DISRUPT (**Difficulty 12** minus Iteration Count):

 **10+** Break the loop. Gain +3 Paradox. Loop

shatters. You're free.

 **7-9** Partially break. Released, but all memories

from the looped scene are permanently Fading.

 **6-** Fail. Loop continues. Lose 1 Coherence from

the effort. Try again next iteration. After 10 iterations: loop releases you automatically. All Active Memories become Fading. Reduce Paradox by **1d6**. Gain Scar: Recursive Doubt.

**Scionfall: The Nullwave Protocol**

A Scionfall Herald has manifested. The Nullwave field expands around you. Reality is draining of color, sound, meaning. The Herald offers cessation one final time. Define what you're trying to hold onto: a specific Memory, a person you're trying to reach, a task you're trying to complete, or your own sense of purpose.

**THE DRAIN**

Each round, describe one sense or aspect of reality fading — colors washing to grey, sounds becoming muffled, touch losing sensation, emotions flattening, meaning eroding from words. Roll **2d6** + ENDURE (**Difficulty 10**):

 **10+** Resist. Maintain coherence through will or

passion. No loss this round. Herald observes, patient.

 **7-9** Partially affected. Lose 1 Coherence. One

Fading Memory becomes Lost. Herald asks again: Why continue?

 **6-** The Nullwave reaches deep. Lose 2 Coherence. Either one Active Memory becomes Fading, or you roll next round with **-2** penalty.

**Critical Failure (snake eyes, 1+1):** you begin to accept. Next round, roll ENDURE with **-4** penalty. If you fail again, you choose cessation — game ends.

**Escape:** Spend **3 Coherence** and invoke your Locked Memory — the one thing you absolutely cannot lose. This creates enough emotional mass to spike your waveform and disrupt the Nullwave. Herald withdraws. Gain Scar: *Hollow Moments*. Scionfall will return during your next Crisis.

Alternatively: generate **+3 Paradox** minimum through an act so violent and contradictory that it disrupts the null field. Herald withdraws, disappointed.

**After 5 rounds:** Herald makes a final offer. One more round if refused. If you survive the 6th round, Herald withdraws — you've proven you're not ready for mercy yet.

---

#### Chronoclasts: Decoherence Bloom Survival

A Chronoclast has detonated a Time Bomb. Local reality has entered superposition — multiple contradictory states existing simultaneously. You're lost in the chaos. Roll **d6** to determine the decoherence:

- **1** = Gravity Reversal (everything falls upward)
- **2** = Temporal Viscosity (time flows like molasses)
- **3** = Language Inversion (everyone speaks backwards)
- **4** = Object Phasing (solid matter becomes permeable)
- **5** = Causal Chaos (actions have random or delayed effects)
- **6** = Quantum Multiplication (everyone splits into 3 simultaneous versions)

Navigation: each action, roll **2d6** + OBSERVE (**Difficulty 10**):

 **10+** Navigate expertly. Find a stable path. No

cost.

 **7-9** Progress, but exposure. Move toward

escape but gain +1 Paradox.

 **6-** Lost. Lose **1d3** Coherence. No progress.

Every 3 rounds, the Chronoclast evaluates you. Roll **d6**: 1 = bored (they make it worse, another decoherence effect stacks), 2 = disappointed (they abandon you, escape becomes **Difficulty 8**), **3-4** = amused (they offer cryptic advice, +2 to next roll), 5 = impressed (they offer to help — automatic success on next roll, but you're Marked), 6 = inspired (they applaud and gift you an unstable Asset). After 5 successful navigation rolls (10+), you find the edge of the decoherence bloom and escape. Gain Scar: Probability Sight — you occasionally see multiple outcomes simultaneously, which causes vertigo and indecision.

## Appendix F: Examples of Play

These examples show how mechanics translate into fiction. They demonstrate when to roll, how to interpret Oracles, how to track resources, and how to write in your Chronicle. The character is Dr. Sarah Martinez, a climate scientist from 2089 Miami, played across a sample campaign.

---

#### Example 1: First Arrival

My Echo is Dr. Sarah Martinez. She's just Displaced — doesn't know when or where she is yet.

I open my eyes. The hurricane's roar is gone. I'm lying on cobblestones in an alley. The air smells wrong — coal smoke and horse manure instead of ocean salt and electric ozone. My grandmother's compass is clutched in my hand, the needle spinning wildly. Through the alley opening, I see gas lamps, horse-drawn carriages, people in Victorian clothing.

I need to figure out when and where I am. The outcome is uncertain, so I roll.

**RESOLUTION ROLL**

- Mode: **OBSERVE** (I'm analyzing my surroundings)
- Memory Bonus: **+2** (Active Memory — 'Scuba Diving the Dying Reef,' tag: Observation)
- Roll: **2d6** = 8, total **8 + 1 + 2 = 11**
- Result: **10+** — Complete Success

I recognize the architecture, the clothing styles, the technology level. Late 19th century, probably London. Victorian era, 1880s-1890s.

On **10+**: gain **+1 Coherence**. Coherence: +3 → +4.

But as I stand, a police constable is staring at me from the alley entrance. My shelter suit is dying — flickering, power almost gone. He's reaching for his whistle.

**Chronicle Entry:**

> **DAY 1 — FIRST DISPLACEMENT**
>
> *Location:* Victorian London, approximately 1885-1895 (uncertain exact year)
>
> *Arrival:* Cobblestone alley near dockside. Coal smoke everywhere.
>
> *Complication:* Constable approaching. Shelter suit dying.
>
> Coherence: +4 (gained 1 from successful identification)
> Paradox: 0 (haven't done anything paradoxical yet)

---

#### Example 2: Social Encounter

The constable blows his whistle. I pull off the dying shelter suit, revealing my regular clothes underneath. I stuff the suit behind a crate.

"Officer! Thank goodness. I was robbed. The ruffian took my coat and purse!"

I'm attempting to deceive and defuse — this needs a roll.

**RESOLUTION ROLL**

Mode: SYNC (social deception, building trust) Memory Bonus: +2 (Active Memory — 'Peer Review Presentation,' tag: Persuasion) Roll: **2d6** = 9, total 9 + 1 + 2 = 12 Result: **12+** — Complete Success (and high enough to count) The constable's suspicion melts immediately. "Robbed? In broad daylight? Those dockside hooligans truly have no shame..." He helps me stand, brushing off my clothes, offering to escort me to the station.

I extract myself politely. On **10+**: gain +1 Coherence. Coherence: +4 →+5. Example 3: Navigation Failure I attempt Precision Navigation to 1851 London — the year of the Great Exhibition, when scientific societies gathered. Somewhere I could use my knowledge.

**PRECISION NAVIGATION**

Target: 1851, London, The Great Exhibition Target Precision: Year + City = **Difficulty 10** Cost: 1 Coherence paid before rolling. Coherence: +5 →+4 Mode: OBSERVE (sensing temporal currents) Memory Bonus: +2 (Active Memory — 'The Shelter Malfunction,' tag: Technology) Roll: **2d6** = 3, total 3 + 1 + 2 = 6 Result: **6-** — Lost in Transit Navigation failed. I must roll all four Anomaly Tables. Consequence: choose Lose 1 Coherence OR Mark +2 Paradox. I choose Coherence loss (keep Paradox low). Coherence: +4 →+3.

**ANOMALY TABLE ROLLS**

ERA (**d100**): 47 →INDUSTRIAL (1800-1850) LOCATION (**d100**): 29 →ACADEMIC INSTITUTION ANOMALY (**d100**): 22 →PROPHETIC RESONANCE COMPLICATION (**d100**): 67 →TEMPORAL SICKNESS (Personal) Interpretation: Cambridge University, approximately 1842. Something terrible is scheduled to happen tomorrow — everyone here knows it with prophetic certainty. They're debating whether to try to prevent it or accept fate. And I just materialized in their library, glowing faintly with temporal radiation sickness. "She's the catalyst," one student whispers. "The warning said a woman in strange clothes — Chronicle Entry:

**DAY 1 — DISPLACEMENT FAILURE**

Attempted Navigation to 1851 London. FAILED. Cost: 2 Coherence total (1 for attempt, 1 for consequence) Landed: Cambridge University, 1842 (Industrial Era) ANOMALY: Prophetic Resonance — everyone knows tomorrow's disaster COMPLICATION: Temporal Sickness — I'm visibly contaminated Current: Coherence **+3**, Paradox **0** Next session: survive the sickness, find out what happens tomorrow

---

#### Example 4: Faction Encounter

Several sessions later. Paradox is now at **7** (Anomaly band). Sarah is in Paris, 1871 — post-Commune chaos. She rolls **7-9** on a Resolution roll. At **Paradox 7-9**, Agents appear as complications on **7-9** results. Roll **d4** for Faction: result = 2 (Loop Authority).

A forgettable person materializes mid-conversation. Average height, average build, clothing that shifts slightly between blinks. They're taking notes on a device that shouldn't exist for 130 years. "Dr. Martinez," they say, voice flat. "You're glitching. We can smooth you out. Painless."

The Authority's Offer: normalize one Active Memory (bonus drops from **+2** to **+0**, emotional context erased) → Reduce Paradox by **2**, clear **1 Stress** from one Asset. Sarah's options: Accept, Refuse, or Drive Off. She refuses. "No. I'm not letting you erase Elena. I'm not letting you normalize any of this."

Consequence: they Mark her (**-1** to Navigation until next Downtime), and begin preparing a Clone Loop (**Difficulty 8** instead of 10 next time Paradox reaches **10+**).

**CHRONICLE NOTE: MARKED — LOOP**

**AUTHORITY**

They're preparing a Clone Loop specifically for me. **Difficulty 8** to trap me (reduced from standard 10). Next time Authority would appear, they appear automatically. I kept Elena's birthday. I kept everything. Ask me if it was worth it when I'm in the Loop.

---

#### Example 5: Downtime

End of session. Coherence: **+3**. Paradox: **7**. Location: Cambridge 1842, Prophetic Resonance still active.

**STEP 1: CHRONICLE (+1 COHERENCE)**

Write session summary in Chronicle. Effect: Coherence +3 →+4.

**STEP 2: REINFORCE ANCHOR**

Anchor took no Stress this session. Skip.

**STEP 3: TEND ASSETS**

Temporal Compass: no Stress marked. No repair needed.

**STEP 4: PROCESS MEMORY**

Nothing significant enough happened this session to create a new Memory. Nothing shifts.

**STEP 5: REDUCE PARADOX (OPTIONAL)**

At Paradox 7, Paradox is urgent. Attempt Temporal Grounding. Roll **2d6** + SYNC (**Difficulty 10**): result = 8 (7-9). Reduce Paradox by 1. Paradox: 7 →6 (out of Anomaly band, back to Flux).

**STEP 6: PLAN NEXT MOVE**

Answer: What am I afraid will happen next? I'm afraid tomorrow's prophesied disaster involves me. I'm afraid I can't stop it without generating more Paradox. I'm afraid that I'm the catastrophe.

**END OF SESSION STATE**

Coherence: +4 (Flux — no modifier) Paradox: 6 (Flux — Scouts on 6-, -1 to rolls) Location: Cambridge 1842, Prophetic Resonance active Assets: Temporal Compass functional Memories: 5 Active, 0 Fading, 0 Locked Next: face tomorrow's prophesied disaster

## Appendix G: Temporal Pathologies

### The Mutation Catalog

**[ALAN]**

*Mutations are what's left when a Scar finishes consuming itself and leaves something working in its place. Most of them are useful. None of them are reversible.*

— AR

**1. Time-Stutter Speech.** *You speak with a quarter-second delay between intent and articulation. To you it sounds like normal speech. To the listener it sounds like you are reading from cue cards held just out of frame. The first time someone called me out on this I'd been doing it for two years. — AR*

**2. Probability Sight.** *You see Paradox as nausea. Unstable people, unstable rooms, unstable moments — they all produce the same low-grade vertigo. Useful. Exhausting. You will learn to leave rooms half a sentence before anyone else does.*

**3. Asymmetric Memory.** *Half of any new memory imprints normally. The other half imprints to the opposite hemisphere of where it should go. You remember every face you've ever seen, but not which side of the face you saw first. Reading is fine. Writing is harder.*

**4. Resonance Bleeding.** *Strong emotions in others register as physical pressure in you. Crowds are oceans. One-on-one conversations are tidal. I avoid weddings. I went to one in 2041. I have not recovered. — AR*

**5. Phantom Calibration.** *Your sense of time is permanently four-and-a-half seconds ahead of consensus reality. Every clock you see is wrong. You learn to compensate. You will never trust a clock again.*

**6. The Quiet.** *Background sound — refrigerator hum, distant traffic, the rustle of leaves — is gone. The world is silent in the parts where it used to murmur. Speech is fine. Music is fine. The murmur of the world that you stopped noticing as a child is permanently absent. You did not realize how much you needed it.*

**7. Spectral Eye.** *One eye sees Paradox as blue phosphorescence. The eye is not the same eye it used to be. Don't ask. — AR*

**8. Recursive Hand.** *Your dominant hand sometimes performs the action you were going to perform a moment before you decide to perform it. You are still in control. The hand is just slightly faster.*

**9. Loop-Echo Hearing.** *You hear your own footsteps a half-second after taking them. You hear other people's footsteps in real time. Most Echoes with Loop-Echo Hearing develop a slight limp because the body tries to walk on the rhythm of the echo and trips itself.*

**10. Calibrated Forgetting.** *You forget specific things on a schedule. Wednesday mornings: the names of people you have not seen in a year. The first night of every season: the smell of the place you grew up. The forgetting is precise. It is not a malfunction. Something is doing it on purpose.*

**11. Faction Sensitivity.** *You can feel when a Faction Agent is within 200 meters of you. Useful. Also: you can feel when one is leaving. Knowing they were watching for the past hour is worse than not knowing.*

**12. Anchor Tunneling.** *When your Anchor Connection is in distress, you sense it. Not symbolically — physically. Headache, nausea, sometimes a pulled muscle in the side of the body that corresponds to where the person is geographically located. Most Echoes with Anchor Tunneling stop using it because the data is unbearable.*

**13. The Slow Ear.** *Speech directed at you takes a perceptible moment to resolve into language. People assume you're processing or thinking. You're not. You're waiting for their words to finish translating themselves into something you can hear.*

**14. Mirror Lag.** *Your reflection lags by a quarter-second. You can use the lag as a tell — your reflection's expression sometimes precedes the one you're about to make.*

**15. The Cold Spot.** *A specific volume of space, roughly two cubic feet, anywhere in your immediate environment, is six degrees colder than the rest of the room. You can feel where it is without looking. Other people feel it too but cannot locate it.*

**16. Threshold Confusion.** *You sometimes do not know whether a person is real or remembered. The confusion is brief — usually a second or two — but in that second you respond to a memory as if it were present, and the present moment moves on without you.*

**17. Causal Sympathy.** *When you injure yourself, the injury appears, faintly, on someone you are connected to. They do not feel it. They do not see it. You see it in them. The injury fades from them as yours heals.*

**18. The Lost Word.** *A word you used to use frequently is now permanently inaccessible. You can describe what it means, when you'd use it, where you learned it. You cannot say it. The word is in you somewhere. It does not come out.*

**19. Frequency Bleed.** *Music and ambient tone affect you more than they used to. A wrong note in the room three streets over is felt. You will learn to live with headphones.*

**20. The Witness.** *Once per day, someone who has been dead for at least ten years is briefly visible in your peripheral vision. You will not see them clearly. You will know who they are. They do not interact. They do not recur. They are, you think, checking on you.*

Optional — unlock after **3+ Memory losses** or **Paradox 8+**

### OPTIONAL COMPLICATIONS

Prolonged displacement does things to a mind that don't have names in linear medicine. The conditions below are optional. They are not assigned automatically — a player may choose to roll on this table when a Memory becomes Lost, or when Paradox reaches **8+**, if they want a more specific shape to their Echo's deterioration. Roll **d6**, or choose the condition that fits your Echo's current state.

---

#### 1 — Cotard's Delusion

You are certain, with absolute clarity, that you are already dead. Your body is a corpse being puppeted by temporal residue. This is not a crisis. It is simply a fact you've accepted. The rot is merely slow.

*Mechanical effect:* you are immune to fear-based intimidation and to the Scionfall Herald's opening offer (you're already dead — cessation holds no terror). However, you cannot gain Coherence from social connection, rest, or comfort. You can only gain Coherence by documenting evidence of your own death in your Chronicle — finding your own grave, reading your own obituary, meeting someone who attended your funeral.

*To remove:* survive a Crisis and roll **12+** on the resolution roll.

---

#### 2 — Fregoli Delusion

Everyone you meet is the same person in a different disguise. The shopkeeper, the soldier, the woman on the train, the Faction Agent — all one entity, cycling through masks, watching you. You're not certain who it is. You're not certain it isn't you.

*Mechanical effect:* you cannot use the SYNC mode to build genuine trust with any new NPC — you can still manipulate, but not connect. Once per session, when an NPC acts against your interests, you may declare 'I knew it was you' — you gain **+1** on your next roll against them, but also gain **+1 Paradox** from the paranoid resonance.

*To remove:* form a genuine Recurring Thread with someone and protect them at personal cost.

---

#### 3 — Palinopsia (Temporal Afterimages)

You see the ghost of every action before it's completed — a visual echo of the recent past, overlapping the present. People are trailed by where they just were. You can see the moment before the punch lands.

*Mechanical effect:* once per session, before any roll, you may declare you are watching the afterimage of this moment. You may reroll one die and take the better result. However, the cognitive load is cumulative — every time you use this ability in a session after the first, lose **1 Coherence** from the strain of double-vision.

*To remove:* spend a full Downtime in complete darkness.

---

#### 4 — The Glass Voice

When you speak about a specific period of your past — usually the period surrounding your most significant Loss — your voice takes on a metallic, ringing quality. You can hear it. Others can hear it. The Church finds it beautiful.

*Mechanical effect:* **-1** to SYNC rolls when the conversation touches on the affected period. However, once per session, you may lean into the Glass Voice deliberately — describe speaking about that period with raw honesty. The authenticity creates an involuntary resonance. Gain **+2** to one SYNC roll immediately following. Church Templars who hear the Glass Voice are momentarily distracted (**-1** to their Drive Off roll against you this encounter).

*To remove:* Lock a new Memory that postdates the loss.

---

#### 5 — Mirror Agnosia

You no longer recognize the person in reflective surfaces as yourself. The recognition mechanism is simply gone — you see a stranger. Sometimes the stranger moves on a slight delay. You've stopped looking.

*Mechanical effect:* you cannot use reflective surfaces to gather information (normally a free OBSERVE action). At **Paradox 7+**, reflections show you a version of yourself from another timeline — this version has different Scars. You may ask one question of this version and receive a truthful answer, but gain **+1 Paradox** from the contact.

*To remove:* maintain **Anchor Strength 4+** for three consecutive sessions.

---

#### 6 — Chronal Aphasia

Your internal sense of sequence has fractured. You know what happened but not when. Events from decades apart feel simultaneous. You lose track of which wounds are old and which are new.

*Mechanical effect:* during Downtime, before rolling to Reinforce your Anchor, roll **1d6**. On a **1-2**, you accidentally reinforce the wrong period — spend the Coherence but gain no benefit (you were thinking of a time that no longer holds meaning). On a **5-6**, you reinforce something deeper than intended — gain **+2 Coherence** instead of the normal benefit. The Oracle decides which period you accessed.

*To remove:* reduce Paradox to 0.

## Appendix H: Recovered Testimony — The Saul Files

**[CHEN]**

*The pages that follow were not part of the original manuscript. They arrived after. A man who was not the man whose name he used spent fourteen months building a record of an event he was not present for, in a name he did not own, because the name fit better than anything he had been called before. He filed fifteen reports. He stopped at fifteen. We have arranged them here in chronological order, lightly annotated, because they belong with the rest of what this book is.*

— EC

**[Z]**

*He kept looking. That is the thing the original could not do. The original froze. The journalist who took his name could not stop. He is in this book because he earned a place in it.*

— Fragment

